Note:
ARM32 Register Allocator - Architecture-Specific Constraint Resolution

Resolves ARM32 register allocation constraints after middle-end graph coloring.
ARM32 has 16 general-purpose registers (R0-R15) where R13=SP, R14=LR, R15=PC
are reserved, leaving R0-R12 for allocation.

ARM32 is a three-address architecture (unlike x86 two-address), so most
instructions naturally support dest, src1, src2 form. However, there are
specific constraints:
- AAPCS calling convention: R0-R3 for arguments, R0-R1 for return values
- R4-R11 are callee-saved
- R12 (IP) is an intra-procedure-call scratch register
- MUL/MLA: destination must differ from first operand on some ARM variants
- SMULL/UMULL: use register pairs for 64-bit results

Dependencies:
- Imports LIR types for function, block, and instruction structures
- Imports LIRNodes for operand creation and instruction construction
- Imports memory/layout.runa for OWNED HEAP allocation (Tier 3)
- Imports list.runa for collection manipulation
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir.runa" as LIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir_nodes.runa" as LIRNodes
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ARM32 Register Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant REG_R0 as Integer is 0
Constant REG_R1 as Integer is 1
Constant REG_R2 as Integer is 2
Constant REG_R3 as Integer is 3
Constant REG_R4 as Integer is 4
Constant REG_R5 as Integer is 5
Constant REG_R6 as Integer is 6
Constant REG_R7 as Integer is 7
Constant REG_R8 as Integer is 8
Constant REG_R9 as Integer is 9
Constant REG_R10 as Integer is 10
Constant REG_R11 as Integer is 11
Constant REG_R12 as Integer is 12        Note: IP (intra-procedure-call scratch)
Constant REG_SP as Integer is 13         Note: Stack Pointer
Constant REG_LR as Integer is 14         Note: Link Register (return address)
Constant REG_PC as Integer is 15         Note: Program Counter

Note: Aliases
Constant REG_FP as Integer is 11         Note: Frame Pointer (R11)
Constant REG_IP as Integer is 12         Note: Intra-procedure-call scratch

Note: Total registers and allocatable count
Constant ARM32_GPR_COUNT as Integer is 16
Constant ARM32_ALLOCATABLE_COUNT as Integer is 13   Note: R0-R12

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LIR Opcode Constants (mirrored from LIR for local convenience)
Note: ============================================================================

Constant OP_MOV as Integer is 30001
Constant OP_ADD as Integer is 30100
Constant OP_SUB as Integer is 30101
Constant OP_IMUL as Integer is 30102
Constant OP_IDIV as Integer is 30103
Constant OP_MUL as Integer is 30104
Constant OP_DIV as Integer is 30105
Constant OP_NEG as Integer is 30106
Constant OP_AND as Integer is 30200
Constant OP_OR as Integer is 30201
Constant OP_XOR as Integer is 30202
Constant OP_NOT as Integer is 30203
Constant OP_SHL as Integer is 30300
Constant OP_SHR as Integer is 30301
Constant OP_SAR as Integer is 30302
Constant OP_CALL as Integer is 30520

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Constraint Type Constants
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
ARM32 constraints are different from x86:
- ARM32 is three-address, so no two-address fixup needed for most instructions
- Division on ARM32 (without hardware divide): requires library call (__aeabi_idiv)
- MUL restriction: on ARMv5 and earlier, Rd must differ from Rm (first operand)
- Calling convention: R0-R3 for arguments, R0-R1 for return
- SMULL/UMULL: 64-bit result in two registers (RdLo, RdHi), must be distinct
@End Reasoning

Constant CONSTRAINT_FIXED_REG as Integer is 1       Note: Operand must be in specific register
Constant CONSTRAINT_CLOBBER as Integer is 2          Note: Instruction clobbers specific registers
Constant CONSTRAINT_MUL_DISTINCT as Integer is 3     Note: MUL dest must differ from first operand
Constant CONSTRAINT_CALL_ARGS as Integer is 4        Note: Arguments in R0-R3
Constant CONSTRAINT_CALL_RETURN as Integer is 5      Note: Return value in R0

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ARM32AllocConstraint Type Definition
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "ARM32AllocConstraint":
    instruction_index as Integer
    constraint_type as Integer
    required_register as Integer
    operand_index as Integer
    block_index as Integer
End Type

Note: Size: 5 fields * 8 bytes = 40 bytes per ARM32AllocConstraint

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Register Information Queries
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "is_allocatable_register" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns 1 if the register is available for general allocation
    Note: SP (13), LR (14), PC (15) are reserved
    If reg_id is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg_id is greater than 12:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "is_callee_saved" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: AAPCS: R4-R11 are callee-saved
    If reg_id is greater than or equal to 4:
        If reg_id is less than or equal to 11:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "is_caller_saved" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: AAPCS: R0-R3, R12 are caller-saved (scratch)
    If reg_id is greater than or equal to 0:
        If reg_id is less than or equal to 3:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If reg_id is 12:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "is_argument_register" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: AAPCS: R0-R3 are used for first 4 integer arguments
    If reg_id is greater than or equal to 0:
        If reg_id is less than or equal to 3:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "get_allocatable_registers" returns Integer:
    Note: Returns a List of allocatable register IDs for ARM32
    Note: Order: scratch first (R0-R3, R12), then callee-saved (R4-R11)
    Let regs be List.list_create(16)
    If regs is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: Scratch registers (no save/restore cost)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_R0)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_R1)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_R2)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_R3)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_R12)
    Note: Callee-saved registers
    List.list_append(regs, REG_R4)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_R5)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_R6)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_R7)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_R8)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_R9)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_R10)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_R11)
    Return regs
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Virtual-to-Physical Register Mapping
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "map_virtual_to_physical" that takes virtual_reg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Maps LIR virtual register IDs to ARM32 physical registers
    Note: Returns -1 if the virtual register must be spilled
    If virtual_reg is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If virtual_reg is less than or equal to 12:
        Return virtual_reg
    End If
    Return -1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Constraint Collection
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
ARM32 has fewer architectural constraints than x86:
1. Three-address form means no two-address fixups needed
2. MUL restriction: on some ARM variants, Rd != Rm for MUL Rd, Rm, Rs
3. Division: ARM32 may lack hardware IDIV; uses __aeabi_idiv library call
4. Call convention: arguments must be in R0-R3 before CALL instructions
5. Return values must be moved from R0 after CALL instructions

The constraint collector scans for MUL and CALL instructions only,
as most ARM32 ALU instructions have no register restrictions.
@End Reasoning

Process called "collect_arm32_constraints" that takes lir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If lir_function is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let constraints be List.list_create(32)
    If constraints is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let blocks be __load(lir_function, 32)
    Let block_count be __load(lir_function, 40)

    If blocks is 0:
        Return constraints
    End If
    If block_count is 0:
        Return constraints
    End If

    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be List.list_get(blocks, b)
        If block is not 0:
            Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
            Let inst_count be __load(block, 24)

            If instructions is not 0:
                Let i be 0
                While i is less than inst_count:
                    Let instruction be List.list_get(instructions, i)
                    If instruction is not 0:
                        Let opcode be __load(instruction, 0)

                        Note: MUL restriction: dest must differ from first operand
                        If opcode is OP_MUL:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_MUL_DISTINCT, -1, 0, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                        End If
                        If opcode is OP_IMUL:
                            Set c to create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_MUL_DISTINCT, -1, 0, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                        End If

                        Note: CALL: arguments must be in R0-R3
                        If opcode is OP_CALL:
                            Set c to create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_CALL_ARGS, REG_R0, 1, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                        End If

                        Note: Division uses library call on most ARM32 variants
                        If opcode is OP_IDIV:
                            Note: __aeabi_idiv takes dividend in R0, divisor in R1, returns in R0
                            Let c1 be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_FIXED_REG, REG_R0, 1, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c1)
                            Let c2 be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_FIXED_REG, REG_R1, 2, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c2)
                        End If
                        If opcode is OP_DIV:
                            Set c1 to create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_FIXED_REG, REG_R0, 1, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c1)
                            Set c2 to create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_FIXED_REG, REG_R1, 2, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c2)
                        End If
                    End If

                    Set i to i plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return constraints
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Internal Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "create_constraint" that takes inst_idx as Integer, ctype as Integer, req_reg as Integer, op_idx as Integer, blk_idx as Integer returns Integer:
    Let c be Layout.allocate(40)
    If c is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    __store(c, 0, inst_idx)
    __store(c, 8, ctype)
    __store(c, 16, req_reg)
    __store(c, 24, op_idx)
    __store(c, 32, blk_idx)
    Return c
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Register Copy Insertion
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "insert_register_copy" that takes block as Integer, before_index as Integer, dest_reg as Integer, src_reg as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    If block is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If dest_reg is src_reg:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let mov_instruction be LIRNodes.create_lir_instruction(OP_MOV)
    If mov_instruction is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let dest_operand be LIRNodes.create_register_operand(dest_reg, size)
    If dest_operand is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let src_operand be LIRNodes.create_register_operand(src_reg, size)
    If src_operand is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    __store(mov_instruction, 8, dest_operand)
    __store(mov_instruction, 16, src_operand)
    __store(mov_instruction, 48, block)

    Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
    If instructions is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    List.list_insert_at(instructions, before_index, mov_instruction)

    Let inst_count be __load(block, 24)
    __store(block, 24, inst_count plus 1)

    Let new_count be inst_count plus 1
    Let idx be before_index
    While idx is less than new_count:
        Let inst be List.list_get(instructions, idx)
        If inst is not 0:
            __store(inst, 64, idx)
        End If
        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MUL Distinct Constraint Resolution
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
On ARMv5 and earlier, MUL Rd, Rm, Rs requires Rd != Rm.
If the destination register is equal to the first source, we swap the operands
(MUL is commutative) or insert a MOV to a temporary register.
@End Reasoning

Process called "handle_mul_distinct" that takes lir_function as Integer, instruction as Integer, block as Integer, inst_index as Integer returns Integer:
    If instruction is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If block is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let result_ptr be __load(instruction, 8)
    Let operand1_ptr be __load(instruction, 16)
    Let operand2_ptr be __load(instruction, 24)

    If result_ptr is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If operand1_ptr is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let result_type be __load(result_ptr, 0)
    Let op1_type be __load(operand1_ptr, 0)
    If result_type is not 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If op1_type is not 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let dest_reg be __load(result_ptr, 8)
    Let src1_reg be __load(operand1_ptr, 8)

    Note: If dest != src1, constraint is satisfied
    If dest_reg is not src1_reg:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Try swapping operands since MUL is commutative
    If operand2_ptr is not 0:
        Let op2_type be __load(operand2_ptr, 0)
        If op2_type is 1:
            Let src2_reg be __load(operand2_ptr, 8)
            If dest_reg is not src2_reg:
                Note: Swap operand1 and operand2
                __store(instruction, 16, operand2_ptr)
                __store(instruction, 24, operand1_ptr)
                Return 0
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Both operands are the same as dest; use R12 (IP) as temp
    Let success be insert_register_copy(block, inst_index, REG_IP, src1_reg, 4)
    If success is 1:
        __store(operand1_ptr, 8, REG_IP)
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Division Constraint Resolution
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
ARM32 without hardware divide uses __aeabi_idiv (signed) or __aeabi_uidiv (unsigned).
Arguments: dividend in R0, divisor in R1
Return: quotient in R0, remainder in R1 (for __aeabi_idivmod)

We insert MOV instructions to place dividend in R0 and divisor in R1, then
replace the IDIV/DIV instruction with a BL __aeabi_idiv/__aeabi_uidiv call.
@End Reasoning

Process called "handle_division_constraint" that takes lir_function as Integer, instruction as Integer, block as Integer, inst_index as Integer returns Integer:
    If instruction is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If block is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be __load(instruction, 0)
    Let result_ptr be __load(instruction, 8)
    Let operand1_ptr be __load(instruction, 16)
    Let operand2_ptr be __load(instruction, 24)

    Let inserted_count be 0

    Note: Move dividend to R0
    If operand1_ptr is not 0:
        Let op1_type be __load(operand1_ptr, 0)
        If op1_type is 1:
            Let dividend_reg be __load(operand1_ptr, 8)
            If dividend_reg is not REG_R0:
                Let s be insert_register_copy(block, inst_index plus inserted_count, REG_R0, dividend_reg, 4)
                If s is 1:
                    Set inserted_count to inserted_count plus 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Move divisor to R1
    If operand2_ptr is not 0:
        Let op2_type be __load(operand2_ptr, 0)
        If op2_type is 1:
            Let divisor_reg be __load(operand2_ptr, 8)
            If divisor_reg is not REG_R1:
                Set s to insert_register_copy(block, inst_index plus inserted_count, REG_R1, divisor_reg, 4)
                If s is 1:
                    Set inserted_count to inserted_count plus 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: After the call, result is in R0. If dest != R0, insert MOV.
    If result_ptr is not 0:
        Let result_type be __load(result_ptr, 0)
        If result_type is 1:
            Let dest_reg be __load(result_ptr, 8)
            If dest_reg is not REG_R0:
                Let after_idx be inst_index plus inserted_count plus 1
                Set s to insert_register_copy(block, after_idx, dest_reg, REG_R0, 4)
                If s is 1:
                    Set inserted_count to inserted_count plus 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Reindex instructions
    Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
    Let total_count be __load(block, 24)
    Let idx be inst_index
    While idx is less than total_count:
        Let inst be List.list_get(instructions, idx)
        If inst is not 0:
            __store(inst, 64, idx)
        End If
        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While

    Return inserted_count
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Complete Constraint Resolution Pass
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "resolve_arm32_constraints" that takes lir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If lir_function is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let constraints be collect_arm32_constraints(lir_function)
    If constraints is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let constraint_count be List.list_length(constraints)
    If constraint_count is 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Process constraints in reverse order
    Let ci be constraint_count minus 1
    While ci is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let constraint be List.list_get(constraints, ci)
        If constraint is not 0:
            Let inst_idx be __load(constraint, 0)
            Let ctype be __load(constraint, 8)
            Let blk_idx be __load(constraint, 32)

            Let blocks be __load(lir_function, 32)
            Let block be List.list_get(blocks, blk_idx)
            If block is not 0:
                Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
                Let instruction be List.list_get(instructions, inst_idx)
                If instruction is not 0:
                    If ctype is CONSTRAINT_MUL_DISTINCT:
                        handle_mul_distinct(lir_function, instruction, block, inst_idx)
                    End If
                    If ctype is CONSTRAINT_FIXED_REG:
                        Let req_reg be __load(constraint, 16)
                        Let op_idx be __load(constraint, 24)
                        handle_fixed_reg_constraint(instruction, block, inst_idx, req_reg, op_idx)
                    End If
                    If ctype is CONSTRAINT_CALL_ARGS:
                        handle_call_args_constraint(lir_function, instruction, block, inst_idx)
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set ci to ci minus 1
    End While

    Note: Coalesce redundant moves
    coalesce_moves(lir_function)

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Fixed Register and Call Argument Constraint Handlers
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "handle_fixed_reg_constraint" that takes instruction as Integer, block as Integer, inst_index as Integer, required_reg as Integer, operand_index as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Moves the specified operand into the required physical register
    Let operand_offset be 16 plus (operand_index multiplied by 8)
    If operand_index is 0:
        Set operand_offset to 8
    End If

    Let operand_ptr be __load(instruction, operand_offset)
    If operand_ptr is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let op_type be __load(operand_ptr, 0)
    If op_type is not 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current_reg be __load(operand_ptr, 8)
    If current_reg is required_reg:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let success be insert_register_copy(block, inst_index, required_reg, current_reg, 4)
    If success is 1:
        __store(operand_ptr, 8, required_reg)
    End If
    Return success
End Process

Process called "handle_call_args_constraint" that takes lir_function as Integer, instruction as Integer, block as Integer, inst_index as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Moves call arguments into R0-R3 as required by AAPCS
    Note: Arguments beyond 4 are pushed onto the stack
    Note: This is handled at a higher level during instruction selection
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Move Coalescing
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "coalesce_moves" that takes lir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If lir_function is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let blocks be __load(lir_function, 32)
    Let block_count be __load(lir_function, 40)
    If blocks is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let removed_count be 0
    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be List.list_get(blocks, b)
        If block is not 0:
            Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
            Let inst_count be __load(block, 24)
            If instructions is not 0:
                Let i be inst_count minus 1
                While i is greater than or equal to 0:
                    Let inst be List.list_get(instructions, i)
                    If inst is not 0:
                        Let opcode be __load(inst, 0)
                        If opcode is OP_MOV:
                            Let result_ptr be __load(inst, 8)
                            Let operand1_ptr be __load(inst, 16)
                            If result_ptr is not 0:
                                If operand1_ptr is not 0:
                                    Let r_type be __load(result_ptr, 0)
                                    Let o_type be __load(operand1_ptr, 0)
                                    If r_type is 1:
                                        If o_type is 1:
                                            Let r_reg be __load(result_ptr, 8)
                                            Let o_reg be __load(operand1_ptr, 8)
                                            If r_reg is o_reg:
                                                List.list_remove_at(instructions, i)
                                                Let new_count be __load(block, 24)
                                                __store(block, 24, new_count minus 1)
                                                Set removed_count to removed_count plus 1
                                            End If
                                        End If
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                    Set i to i minus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If
        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return removed_count
End Process
